  "prompt": "Does a voltmeter show RMS voltage?",
  "response": "Yes, most modern voltmeters, particularly digital multimeters (DMMs), are designed to display the root mean square (RMS) voltage of alternating current (AC) signals. The RMS value is a useful representation because it provides an equivalent DC voltage that would deliver the same power to a load.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that not all voltmeters are created equal. Some older or basic analog voltmeters may not accurately measure the RMS value of non-sinusoidal waveforms (like square waves, triangular waves, or other complex waveforms). They may provide a reading based on the average voltage or some other calculation, which may not reflect the true power capability of the signal.\n\nTo summarize, if you're using a modern DMM or a true RMS voltmeter, it will typically show you the RMS voltage. Always refer to the specifications of the voltmeter to ensure it meets your measurement needs, especially for non-sinusoidal waveforms.",
